Part 1: Introduction

The data were obtained in a survey of students Portuguese language courses in secondary school. It contains a lot of interesting social, gender and study information about students. We can use it for some EDA or answer some questions to predict students class performance.

Data Source: (https://www.kaggle.com/uciml/student-alcohol-consumption)

Variable Meanings

  • school - students school (binary: GP - Gabriel Pereira or MS - Mousinho da Silveira)

  • sex - students sex (binary: F - female or M - male)

  • age - students age (numeric: from 15 to 22)

  • address - students home address type (binary: U - urban or R - rural)

  • famsize - family size (binary: LE3 - less or equal to 3 or GT3 - greater than 3)

  • Pstatus - parents cohabitation status (binary: T - living together or A - apart)

  • Medu - mothers education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 5th to 9th grade, 3 secondary education or 4 higher education)

  • Fedu - fathers education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 5th to 9th grade, 3 secondary education or 4 higher education)

  • Mjob - mothers job (nominal: teacher, health care related, civil services (e.g.administrative or police), at_home or other)

  • Fjob - fathers job (nominal: teacher, health care related, civil services (e.g.administrative or police), at_home or other)

  • reason - reason to choose this school (nominal: close to home, school reputation, course preference or other)

  • guardian - students guardian (nominal: mother, father or other)

  • traveltime - home to school travel time (numeric: 1 - 1 hour)

  • studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - 10 hours)

  • failures - number of past class failures (numeric: n if 1<=n<3, else 4)

  • schoolsup - extra educational support (binary: yes or no)

  • famsup - family educational support (binary: yes or no)

  • paid - extra paid classes within the course subject (Math or Portuguese) (binary: yes or no)

  • activities - extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no)

  • nursery - attended nursery school (binary: yes or no)

  • higher - wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)

  • internet - Internet access at home (binary: yes or no)

  • romantic - with a romantic relationship (binary: yes or no)

  • famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)

  • freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  • goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  • Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  • Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)

  • health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)

  • absences - number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)

These grades are related with the course subject, Math or Portuguese:

  • G1 - first period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  • G2 - second period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
  • G3 - final grade (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)

Part 4: EDA

Explore the Data

#Data exploratory 
#Which school has the most study times?
ranking <- group_by(students.df, school) %>%
         summarize(students.df = mean(studytime)) %>%
         as.data.frame %>% arrange(desc(students.df))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
head(ranking, 2)
##   school students.df
## 1     GP    2.014184
## 2     MS    1.774336

Observation: We can see that GPs students spend the most time studying. The average of GP is 2 hours, compared to MS which is closed to 2 as well.

EDA visualizations

Observations: both schools, students are between the ages of 16 and 19 years old. Among the two schools, the students spend similar amounts of time studying , on average 2 hours is spent studying. The students within this dataset miss fewer days of school, as we can see the histogram is heavily right-skewed. GP school has more students than MP, but both schools seem to be predominantly female.

Do students who do not participate in extracurricular activities drink more during the workday?

  geom_bar(position="dodge")
p19 + geom_bar(stat = "count", position = "dodge") + 
  labs(title = "Workday Alcohol Consumption by Activities",  x = "Workweek Alcohol Consumption - Dalc (1 - Very Low to 5 - Very High)", y = "Number of Students")

Observations: This graph shows that, within this dataset, slightly more students who participated in extracurricular activities consume very high amounts of alcohol during the workday compared to students who do not participate in extracurricular actvities. It also shows that slightly more students who do not participate in extracurricular activities consume very low amounts of alcohol compared to those who do participate in extracurricular activities.

Do males consume more alcohol during the workday compared to females?

MAIN QUESTION: How Does Alcohol Consumption Correlate with Gender and Class Performance?

Firstly, we can look into the final results by gender. Lets see if they are approximately the same within schools or whether the performance is different between female and male gender.

How is Student Performance Related to Gender?

#data manipulation

MS <- filter(students.df, school == "MS")
Students <- rbind(GP, MS)

  labs(title = "Student Performance by School by Gender",

Observations: Approximately 75% of male students perform not good as the median female student, and except for a few outliers, all male students perform worse than the top quarter of female students. From this, we can question if there are any reasons female scores better in the language class than male ? Should the school change the teaching way to help male better in this class ?

Part 9: Conclusions

From all the observations that we have, there is definitely a factor that affects the students weekday alcohol consumption. Students that have more free time and parents in high demanding jobs tend to drink more than students whose parents stay at home. Moreover, students that have family greater than 3 tends to drink more, but the students that have parents occupation in health field and in family less than 3 drink more than others occupation fields.
